      "header": "Long-Running Operations & Job Persistence",
      "content": "### Long-Running Operations & Job Persistence\n- **In-memory job state survives deploys trap**: Job tracking via JavaScript `Map()` or module-level variables gets wiped on every deploy; long-running operations (3-6 min) fail with \"session expired\" or 404 when frontend polls for status post-deploy; fix: persist job metadata to PostgreSQL table (`generation_jobs`, `processing_jobs`, etc.) with job ID, status, timestamps, and output; enables job lookup after redeploy without data loss; frontend polling finds completed work even if server restarted mid-operation\n- **Job persistence migration pattern**: Create table with job_id (UUID primary key), status enum (queued/processing/completed/failed), created_at, updated_at, output (text/JSON for results); CRUD endpoints: POST to create, GET by job_id to poll status, DELETE to cleanup; survives deploys, supports concurrent job tracking, enables retry-tolerance on frontend for brief connectivity blips\n- **Polling window calculations for long-running operations**: Frontend polls backend for operation status with max polls and interval; total window = maxPolls × pollInterval; for operations taking 3-6 minutes (like multi-phase AI generation or bulk enrichment), use 120-150 polls at 3-second intervals (6-7.5 minutes total); leave 1-2 minute safety margin above expected completion; window must accommodate network delays and API response times\n- **Cron job patterns with node-cron**: Schedule recurring tasks (bounce detection, weekly digests, cleanup jobs) with `cron.schedule('pattern', callback)` in server.js; cron jobs survive app restarts and run on fixed schedules; pattern examples: `'0 9 * * 1'` (Monday 9am UTC), `'*/5 * * * *'` (every 5 minutes); jobs persist across deploys, making them suitable for batch operations tied to business logic",
